==English==

===Etymology===
{{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|bevrage|lang=fro}}, from {{term|boivre||to drink|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|bibō}}. Cognate to {{term|imbibe|lang=en}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|en-us-beverage.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A [[liquid]] to [[consume]], usually excluding [[water]]; a [[drink]]. This may include tea, coffee, liquor, beer, milk, juice, or soft drinks.
#* Thomson
#*: He knew no '''beverage''' but the flowing stream.
# {{context|slang|archaic|lang=en}} A [[treat]], or [[drink]] [[money]].

====Usage notes====
* More elevated than plainer {{term|drink}}. ''Beverage'' is of French origin, while ''drink'' is of Old English origin, and this stylistic difference by origin is common; see {{w|list of English words with dual French and Anglo-Saxon variations}}.
* The word ''beverage'' is rarely used in British English.

